uctor that throws a checked exception instead. But am I limited by ByteBuffer's constructors being package-private? That complicates subclassing, so using Constructor<ByteBuffer> with a valid subclass might be my next step.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering DirectByteBuffer Usage**\\n\\nI’m thinking about using the existing DirectByteBuffer constructor if it’s available in older JDKs, but it looks like it’s not. For the test to pass, if ConstructorProbe isn’t a ByteBuffer, then getDirectBufferAt will throw a ClassCastException. Should I fix the assertion to check for ClassCastException instead? But that might push the message outside the catch block. However, a dynamic call would still be covered. Still, direct field reflection could violate the test's integrity.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_jX7VMZ5f3kp5rUm8cRZFeKP7|fc_0c1c7e0be1555f760169f2a1d4cf5481a0adc074787c51157b", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/com.esotericsoftware/kryo-shaded/3.0.3/src/test/java/com_esotericsoftware/kryo_shaded/UnsafeUtilTest.java", "limit": 160}, "partialJson": "{\"path\":\"tests/src/com.esotericsoftware/kryo-shaded/3.0.3/src/test/java/com_esotericsoftware/kryo_shaded/UnsafeUtilTest.java\",\"limit\":160}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 994, "output": 882, "cacheRead": 43008, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 44884, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777508807076, "responseId": "resp_0c1c7e0be1555f760169f2a1c7f87481a094db5bc1eb052797"}}
