unsafe = UnsafeUtil.unsafe();\n        long address = 0L;\n        boolean allocated = false;\n        int size = unsafe == null ? 0 : MEMORY_SIZE;\n\n        try {\n            if (unsafe != null) {\n                address = unsafe.allocateMemory(MEMORY_SIZE);\n                allocated = true;\n                unsafe.setMemory(address, MEMORY_SIZE, (byte) 0);\n            }\n\n            ByteBuffer buffer = UnsafeUtil.getDirectBufferAt(address, size);\n\n            if (buffer == null) {\n                assertThat(buffer).isNull();\n            } else {\n                assertThat(buffer.isDirect()).isTrue();\n                assertThat(buffer.capacity()).isEqualTo(size);\n                if (unsafe != null) {\n                    buffer.put(0, (byte) 0x2A);\n                    assertThat(unsafe.getByte(address)).isEqualTo((byte) 0x2A);\n                }\n            }\n        } finally {\n            if (allocated) {\n                unsafe.freeMemory(address);\n            }\n        }\n    }\n\n    @Test\n    void reportsAllocationFailureFromCachedDirectBufferConstructor() throws Exception {\n        Field directByteBufferConstructor = UnsafeUtil.class.getDeclaredField(\"directByteBufferConstr\");\n        directByteBufferConstructor.setAccessible(true);\n        Object originalConstructor = directByteBufferConstructor.get(null);\n        Constructor<ConstructorProbe> probeConstructor = ConstructorProbe.class.getConstructor(\n                long.class, int.class, Object.class);\n\n        try {\n            directByteBufferConstructor.set(null, probeConstructor);\n\n            assertThatThrownBy(() -> UnsafeUtil.getDirectBufferAt(1L, 2))\n                    .isInstanceOf(RuntimeException.class)\n                    .hasMessageContaining(\"Cannot allocate ByteBuffer\");\n        } finally {\n            directByteBufferConstructor.set(null, originalConstructor);\n        }\n    }\n\n    public static class ConstructorProbe {\n        private final long address;\n        private final int size;\n        private final Object owner;\n\n        public ConstructorProbe(long address, int size, Object owner) {\n            this.address = address;\n            this.size = size;\n            this.owner = owner;\n        }\n    }\n\n    public static class FieldLayout {\n        private byte first;\n        private long second;\n        private int third;\n        private Object fourth;\n    }\n}\n"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1777508821219}}
[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Analyzing Jacoco and JVM Tests**\n\nI'm trying to understand how Jacoco and dynamic raw data interact. There's a question of whether a line in Jacoco is covered if the call site was executed, even if it's not shown in JVM tests. I'm thinking about whether specific class initialization affects this and if the Jacoco agent starts correctly when tests run. I need to ensure that our tests execute the problematic lines and confirm my assumptions about exceptions being thrown or caught during the process.\n\n**Resolving ByteBuffer Subclassing**\n\nI'm trying to assert if a RuntimeException is thrown, but if the message is null and doesn't contain \"Cannot allocate,\" the test would fail. However, tests might not have run yet. I need to ensure that the ConstructorProbe extends ByteBuffer to pass the cast requirement, but that would require implementing many methods. If there's no exception thrown, maybe I should use a constructor that throws a checked exception instead. But am I limited by ByteBuffer's constructors being package-private? That complicates subclassing, so using Constructor<ByteBuffer> with a valid subclass might be my next step.\n\n**Considering DirectByteBuffer Usage**\n\nI’m thinking about using the existing DirectByteBuffer constructor if it’s available in older JDKs, but it looks like it’s not. For the test to pass, if ConstructorProbe isn’t a ByteBuffer, then getDirectBufferAt will throw a ClassCastException. Should I fix the assertion to check for ClassCastException instead? But that might push the message outside the catch block. However, a dynamic call would still be covered. Still, direct field reflection could violate the test's integrity.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0c1c7e0be1555f760169f2a1c8a55c81a091f9028de7d6b206\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp8qHUdx2-PaOTve28w7vDdRWM0ESid-ylXHZj9X1Y60zvbiHcn61dZ6vXJ0AD